{{ja-kanjitab|つぶり|yomi=irr}}

Cognate with {{m|ja|粒|tr=tsubu||round thing|pos=such as a grain}}, {{m|ja|禿ぶ|tr=tsubu||to go bald|pos=from the idea of one's head becoming ''round''}}, {{m|ja|円ら|tr=tsubura|pos=adjective||round}}, {{m|ja|潰れる|tr=tsubureru||to become rounded, as from wear and tear, or from crushing}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

Some sources<ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref> derive this as a shift from {{m|ja|円ら|tr=tsubura|pos=adjective||round}}.  However, the phonology and semantics for this do not fit (changing {{IPAchar|/a/}} to {{IPAchar|/i/}}, and repurposing the adjectivizing suffix {{m|ja|ら}} to instead form a noun).  The modern verb ''tsubureru'' had the form ''tsuburu'' in older stages of the language.  The ''tsuburi'' reading for {{lang|ja|頭}} may more likely represent a nominalization derived from this older verb, following normal patterns for creating nouns from verbs.

